fr.reflexe.viewshell.api.data

Interface IIntersection

  • All Superinterfaces:
    IAttachable, ICellStructure, IFetchable, IListStructure

    public interface IIntersection
extends IFetchable
    An intersection of one or more data sources provided by a connector. This most commonly involves merging a data set B (the intersection target) with a master data set A (the intersection source), as commonly described using boolean algebra and set theory.

    Use of an intersection is the most efficient way to merge data sets to retrieve normalized data based on relationships (such as merging labels by querying multiple data sources using foreign key relationships).

    Intersections are also used to perform boolean algebra when merging data sets (a logical abstraction of SQL JOIN behavior).

    Note: every intersection must define a unique attachment ID, which must be:

    • different to the attachment ID defined by the master source
    • identical to another other semantically-identical intersection
    • when derived, consistent and deterministic (based on immutable attributes such as the attachment ID, and not on potentially-modifiable attributes such as names).

    Additionally, no intersection may re-use the same cell ID as any other data set (target, source, or master).

    Thread safety: implementations are required to be safe for concurrent read/write access.

    Since:
    1.0
    Author:
    REFLEXE Technologies
    See Also:
    IConnector.getIntersection(java.util.UUID), IListView

      • on

        IIntersection on(ICell sourceCell,
                 ICell targetCell)
        Specifies the cells used to define an equality-based intersection relationship.

        For simple relationships (such as foreign key to primary key), this should be called only once (multiple calls with the same parameters are ignored). For composite relationships, this will need to be called multiple times, to fully define the unique combination of cells defining the relationship.

        It is not necessary to call this for cross joins.

        In terms of SQL, this represents an EQUI-JOIN.

        Note: THETA-JOINS (where the intersection is not equality-based) are not directly implemented in this version of the API.

        Parameters:
        sourceCell - the cell in the source data set A participating in the association.
        targetCell - the cell in the target data set B participating in the association.
        Returns:
        this same intersection instance, enabling method chaining.
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        getRelationships()
